{"id":"2303.04130","submitter":"Daniel Grimmer","authors":"Daniel Grimmer","title":"In Search of New Spacetimes: Spacetime Non-Fundamentality even for\n  Well-Established Physics","comments":"51 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.hist-ph gr-qc","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  What goes into building a spacetime? This paper develops some powerful\nmathematical tools (which I will call the ISE Methodology) for discovering and\nnegotiating between a wide range of alternate spacetime settings for nearly any\nspacetime theory. The mathematics involved is relatively simple (i.e., no\nalgebraic geometry and no category theory). Moreover, the scope of\napplicability is incredibly wide; These simple spacetime re-description\ntechniques are, in principle, applicable to every spacetime theory since\nNewton. Unlike the algebraic approach to spacetime, the ISE Methodology does\nnot use a theory's algebraic structure in order to reconstruct its original\nspacetime manifold. Instead, a wide range of new spacetime settings are offered\nto us, based on nothing but our ability to smoothly vary the theory's states.\nTo build a new spacetime setting for a theory one first picks out a certain\nkind of Lie group action on its states (which I will call pre-spacetime\ntranslation operations). This kind of Lie group action is indistinguishable\nfrom spacetime translations, structurally speaking. Using the techniques\nintroduced in this paper, one can then construct a new spacetime setting for\nthe theory in question such that these pre-spacetime translation operations\nbecome honest-to-goodness spacetime translations in the new theory. These\nspacetime re-description techniques will be demonstrated with three\nillustrative example applications.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 5 Mar 2023 23:47:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-08"}
